            { type: "numeric", difficulty: "medium", q: "If the heart beats 72 times per minute, how many times does it beat in one hour?", answer: "4320", explanation: "72 × 60 = 4320 beats per hour." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "hard", q: "Describe the route oxygenated blood takes from the moment it leaves the lungs until it reaches a muscle cell in the leg.", answer: "Oxygenated blood leaves the lungs via the pulmonary veins, enters the left atrium, passes through the bicuspid (mitral) valve into the left ventricle, which pumps it through the aortic valve into the aorta. It then travels via arteries, to smaller arterioles and finally into capillaries at the muscle cell, where oxygen diffuses out. Deoxygenated blood returns via venules, veins and the vena cava to the right atrium.", explanation: "Left atrium → left ventricle → aorta → arteries → capillaries at muscle cell." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "hard", q: "Explain why blood flows through the heart in two separate circuits ('double circulation') and why the left ventricle has a thicker wall than the right.", answer: "Double circulation means blood passes through the heart twice per loop: the right side pumps deoxygenated blood to the lungs (pulmonary circuit) and the left side pumps oxygenated blood to the whole body (systemic circuit). Keeping them separate stops oxygen-rich and oxygen-poor blood mixing and keeps pressure high. The left ventricle is more muscular because it must generate much higher pressure to push blood all round the body, while the right only pushes to the nearby lungs.", explanation: "Separate circuits prevent mixing; the left ventricle works harder, so it's thicker." },
            { type: "long", difficulty: "hard", q: "A student measures a resting heart rate of 68 bpm and an exercising heart rate of 140 bpm. Explain why heart rate increases during exercise and trace where the extra oxygenated blood goes.", answer: "During exercise muscles contract more often and need more ATP, which requires more oxygen and glucose. The muscles produce more CO₂. Sensors detect the CO₂ rise and the brain (medulla oblongata) speeds up the heart via nerves and adrenaline. The increased heart rate (and stroke volume) pushes more blood per minute through the pulmonary circuit to pick up more oxygen at the lungs, then through the systemic circuit to deliver it to the working muscles. Blood vessels in the muscles dilate (vasodilation) to increase blood flow. The extra CO₂ diffuses from muscle capillaries into the blood and is carried to the lungs to be exhaled.", explanation: "More CO₂ → nervous/hormonal signal → faster heart → more blood to muscles via systemic circuit." }
