            { type: "match", difficulty: "medium", q: "Match each blood component to its main function.", pairs: [["Red blood cells","Transport oxygen using haemoglobin"],["White blood cells","Defend against pathogens"],["Platelets","Form blood clots at wounds"],["Plasma","Carries dissolved substances (glucose, CO2, hormones)"]], explanation: "Each component has a specific role in transport, defence or clotting." },
            { type: "tf", difficulty: "medium", q: "Veins have valves to prevent blood from flowing backwards due to low pressure.", answer: true, explanation: "Without valves, the low pressure in veins would allow blood to pool; valves keep it moving towards the heart." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "medium", q: "The liquid part of blood that transports dissolved substances is called:", options: ["Serum", "Lymph", "Plasma", "Haemoglobin"], answer: 2, explanation: "Plasma is the straw-coloured liquid carrying glucose, CO₂, hormones and proteins." },
            { type: "numeric", difficulty: "medium", q: "A typical red blood cell lives for about how many days?", answer: "120", explanation: "Red blood cells survive approximately 120 days before being broken down in the liver and spleen." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "hard", q: "Compare the structures of arteries, veins and capillaries and explain how each is adapted to its function.", answer: "Arteries have thick, muscular, elastic walls to withstand the high pressure from the heart's pumping. Veins have thinner walls (less muscle/elastic tissue) and valves to prevent backflow as blood travels at low pressure back to the heart. Capillaries are a single cell thick, forming a large network, giving a short diffusion distance and large surface area for exchanging oxygen, glucose and CO₂ between the blood and tissues.", explanation: "Structure matches function: thick-walled arteries (high pressure), valved veins (low pressure), thin capillaries (exchange)." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "hard", q: "Explain how red blood cells are specially adapted to carry oxygen efficiently.", answer: "Red blood cells are biconcave (disc-shaped with a dent on each side), which gives them a large surface area for oxygen diffusion. They have no nucleus, freeing up space for more haemoglobin. Haemoglobin binds oxygen in the lungs (forming oxyhaemoglobin) and releases it in respiring tissues where oxygen concentration is low.", explanation: "Biconcave shape, no nucleus, and haemoglobin all maximise oxygen-carrying capacity." },
            { type: "long", difficulty: "hard", q: "A doctor analyses a patient's blood and finds unusually few red blood cells and low haemoglobin. Predict the symptoms and explain the cause, linking structure and function.", answer: "The condition is anaemia. With fewer red blood cells and less haemoglobin, the blood can carry less oxygen per litre. Tissues do not get enough oxygen for aerobic respiration, so the patient may feel tired, breathless (even at rest), pale (less oxyhaemoglobin in skin), and have a rapid heart rate (the heart compensates by beating faster). Causes include iron deficiency (haemoglobin contains iron), blood loss, or bone marrow not making enough cells. Treatment could include iron supplements or in severe cases a blood transfusion.", explanation: "Fewer/faulty red blood cells → less O₂ transport → tired, breathless, pale, fast heart rate." }
