            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "easy", q: "During exercise, heart rate usually:", options: ["Decreases", "Increases", "Stays exactly the same", "Stops"], answer: 1, explanation: "Muscles need more oxygen and glucose during exercise, so the heart beats faster to deliver it." },
            { type: "tf", difficulty: "easy", q: "A well-trained athlete typically has a lower resting heart rate than an untrained person.", answer: true, explanation: "Regular aerobic training makes the heart more efficient — it pumps more blood per beat, so fewer beats are needed at rest." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "easy", q: "Which hormone is released during stress and exercise to speed up the heart?", options: ["Insulin", "Oestrogen", "Adrenaline", "Glucagon"], answer: 2, explanation: "Adrenaline (epinephrine) prepares the body for 'fight or flight' by increasing heart rate." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "medium", q: "After stopping exercise, heart rate returns to normal because:", options: ["Blood stops moving", "Oxygen demand drops, CO₂ is removed, and the nervous system reduces stimulation", "All valves close", "The heart runs out of fuel"], answer: 1, explanation: "As muscles slow down, less CO₂ is produced and less oxygen is needed, so the control systems slow the heart back to resting rate." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "medium", q: "Name the independent and dependent variables in an investigation of how exercise affects heart rate, and one variable you would control.", answer: "Independent variable: the level/duration of exercise (e.g. minutes of step-ups). Dependent variable: heart rate in beats per minute. Controlled variable (any one): same person, same starting rest period, same way of measuring pulse, same room temperature.", explanation: "Change the exercise (IV), measure heart rate (DV), keep other conditions the same." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "medium", q: "Which factor would NOT typically increase heart rate?", options: ["Exercise", "Stress", "Sleep", "Fever"], answer: 2, explanation: "Sleep lowers heart rate; the others all increase it." },
            { type: "tf", difficulty: "medium", q: "Caffeine can increase heart rate by stimulating the nervous system.", answer: true, explanation: "Caffeine is a stimulant that blocks chemicals that slow the heart, causing a higher heart rate." },
            { type: "numeric", difficulty: "medium", q: "A student's heart rate rises from 70 bpm to 130 bpm during exercise. By how many bpm did it increase?", answer: "60", explanation: "130 − 70 = 60 bpm increase." },
            { type: "match", difficulty: "medium", q: "Match each factor to whether it increases or decreases heart rate.", pairs: [["Exercise","Increases heart rate"],["Sleep","Decreases heart rate"],["Adrenaline","Increases heart rate"],["Regular aerobic training over time","Decreases resting heart rate"]], explanation: "Understanding what raises and lowers heart rate is key to interpreting investigations." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "hard", q: "A student designs an investigation: she does 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5 minutes of step-ups, then measures her heart rate each time. Identify one weakness in this design and suggest an improvement.", answer: "Weakness: she does each exercise bout one after another without returning to resting heart rate between bouts, so later measurements are affected by earlier exercise (confounding variable). Improvement: rest fully (return to resting heart rate) before starting each different duration of exercise, and ideally repeat each condition on separate days or with multiple participants for reliability.", explanation: "Without recovery time between conditions, the variable of residual fatigue confounds the results." },
            { type: "long", difficulty: "hard", q: "Explain why the body needs to increase heart rate AND breathing rate together during intense exercise, linking the cardiovascular and respiratory systems.", answer: "During intense exercise, muscles respire aerobically at a much higher rate and need more oxygen and glucose while producing more CO₂ and water. The cardiovascular and respiratory systems work together to meet this demand. Increased heart rate pumps more blood per minute (higher cardiac output), delivering more oxygen and glucose to muscle cells. At the same time, breathing rate increases so the lungs exchange gases faster — taking in more oxygen and expelling more CO₂. More blood flows through lung capillaries, which are already in contact with higher concentrations of fresh air. CO₂ detected in the blood by the medulla oblongata signals both systems to speed up. If either system fails to keep up, CO₂ builds up and oxygen debt occurs, causing fatigue.", explanation: "Both systems are coordinated: heart delivers blood faster, lungs exchange gases faster, triggered by CO₂ rise." },
            { type: "tf", difficulty: "easy", q: "A person's heart rate is usually higher during exercise than at rest.", answer: true, explanation: "Exercise increases oxygen demand, so the heart beats faster to deliver more oxygenated blood to muscles." }
