            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "easy", q: "High blood pressure is also known as:", options: ["Angina", "Hypertension", "Anaemia", "Arrhythmia"], answer: 1, explanation: "Hypertension means persistently elevated blood pressure, which strains the heart and blood vessels." },
            { type: "tf", difficulty: "easy", q: "Smoking is a risk factor for coronary heart disease.", answer: true, explanation: "Chemicals in cigarette smoke damage artery walls and encourage fatty plaque build-up." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "easy", q: "Angina is chest pain caused by:", options: ["A broken rib", "Insufficient blood flow to the heart muscle", "Lung infection", "Stomach acid"], answer: 1, explanation: "When coronary arteries are narrowed, the heart muscle doesn't get enough oxygen during exertion, causing chest pain (angina)." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "medium", q: "A diet high in saturated fat can lead to fatty deposits narrowing the arteries, increasing the risk of:", options: ["Scurvy", "Coronary heart disease", "Rickets", "Anaemia"], answer: 1, explanation: "Fatty plaques in the coronary arteries reduce blood flow to the heart muscle — coronary heart disease." },
            { type: "tf", difficulty: "medium", q: "Regular exercise and not smoking lower the risk of coronary heart disease.", answer: true, explanation: "Both protect the heart and blood vessels, reducing cardiovascular risk." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "medium", q: "Heart failure means the heart:", options: ["Stops completely forever", "Cannot pump blood efficiently enough to meet the body's needs", "Beats too fast only", "Has too many chambers"], answer: 1, explanation: "Heart failure is when a damaged or weakened heart pumps too little blood, causing fluid build-up and breathlessness." },
            { type: "match", difficulty: "medium", q: "Match each cardiovascular condition to its key feature.", pairs: [["Coronary heart disease","Fatty plaques narrow the coronary arteries"],["Hypertension","Persistently raised blood pressure"],["Angina","Chest pain from reduced blood flow to heart muscle"],["Heart failure","Heart cannot pump efficiently enough"]], explanation: "Each condition involves the cardiovascular system failing in a different way." },
            { type: "tf", difficulty: "medium", q: "A stent is a small wire mesh tube inserted into a narrowed artery to keep it open.", answer: true, explanation: "Stents are a common treatment for coronary heart disease — they prop open the artery to restore blood flow." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "hard", q: "Describe how atherosclerosis develops and explain its link to heart attacks.", answer: "Atherosclerosis begins when the inner lining of an artery is damaged (e.g. by smoking, high blood pressure or high LDL cholesterol). Fatty material (plaque) builds up at the damage site, narrowing the artery and making the wall thicker and less flexible. If a plaque ruptures, a blood clot can form, completely blocking a coronary artery. This cuts off the oxygen supply to heart muscle, causing a myocardial infarction (heart attack).", explanation: "Damaged artery → plaque builds up → possible clot → blocked coronary artery → heart attack." },
            { type: "short", difficulty: "hard", q: "List three lifestyle changes a person could make to reduce their risk of cardiovascular disease, and explain why each helps.", answer: "1. Exercise regularly: strengthens the heart, lowers blood pressure and raises HDL ('good') cholesterol. 2. Eat a diet low in saturated fat and salt: reduces LDL cholesterol and lowers blood pressure, slowing plaque build-up. 3. Stop smoking: removes chemicals that damage artery walls and raise blood pressure, reducing risk of clot formation.", explanation: "Each change targets a different risk factor: pressure, cholesterol, or direct artery damage." },
            { type: "long", difficulty: "hard", q: "A 45-year-old patient is told he has hypertension and high LDL cholesterol. Explain what these mean, what cardiovascular risks they pose, and the treatment options available.", answer: "Hypertension (high blood pressure) means the blood is pressing against artery walls with too much force. This damages the artery lining over time, increasing the risk of atherosclerosis (plaque build-up), aneurysm (bulging weak artery), stroke and heart failure. High LDL (low-density lipoprotein) cholesterol means there is more 'bad' cholesterol in the blood, which deposits in artery walls forming fatty plaques — narrowing arteries and increasing the risk of coronary heart disease and heart attacks. Together these conditions greatly raise cardiovascular risk. Treatment options include: lifestyle changes (diet low in saturated fat, reduced salt, regular exercise, stopping smoking); medication (antihypertensive drugs to lower blood pressure, statins to lower LDL); and in severe artery narrowing, surgical procedures like stenting or coronary bypass surgery.", explanation: "Hypertension damages arteries; high LDL deposits plaques. Both increase heart attack/stroke risk. Treated with lifestyle changes and/or medication." },
            { type: "mcq", difficulty: "easy", q: "Which lifestyle change most directly lowers blood pressure?", options: ["Eating more saturated fat", "Reducing salt intake and exercising regularly", "Sleeping fewer hours", "Eating more processed foods"], answer: 1, explanation: "Reducing salt decreases fluid retention and blood volume, lowering blood pressure; exercise strengthens the heart and reduces arterial resistance." }
